\par }{\rtlch \af0\afs20 \ltrch \fs20\lang2057\langfe1036\cgrid0\langnp2057\insrsid1647885\charrsid1647885 Le format Ogg
\par 
\par A physical Ogg bitstream consists of multiple logical bitstreams
\par    interleaved in so-called "Pages".  Whole pages are taken in order
\par    from multiple logical bitstreams multiplexed at the page level.  The
\par    logical bitstreams are identified by a unique serial number in the
\par    header of each page of the physical bitstream.  This unique serial
\par    number is created randomly and does not have any connection to the
\par    content or encoder of the logical bitstream it represents.
\par 
\par Pages are of variable size and have a page
\par    header containing encapsulation and error recovery information.  Each
\par    logical bitstream in a physical Ogg bitstream starts with a special
\par    start page (bos=beginning of stream) and ends with a special page
\par    (eos=end of stream).
\par 
\par The bos page contains information to uniquely identify the codec type
\par    and MAY contain information to set up the decoding process.  The bos
\par    page SHOULD also contain information about the encoded media - for
\par    example, for audio, it should contain the sample rate and number of
\par    channels.  By convention, the first bytes of the bos page contain
\par    magic data that uniquely identifies the required codec.
\par 
\par   So, a physical bitstream begins with the bos pages of all logical
\par    bitstreams containing one initial header packet per page, followed by
\par    the subsidiary header packets of all streams, followed by pages
\par    containing data packets.
\par 
\par As Ogg pages have a maximum size of
\par    about 64 kBytes, sometimes a packet has to be distributed over
\par    several pages.  To simplify that process, Ogg divides each packet
\par    into 255 byte long chunks plus a final shorter chunk.  These chunks
\par    are called "Ogg Segments".  They are only a logical construct and do
\par    not have a header for themselves.
\par 
\par  Note that a lacing value of 255
\par    implies that a second lacing value follows in the packet, and a value
\par    of less than 255 marks the end of the packet after that many
\par    additional bytes.  A packet of 255 bytes (or a multiple of 255 bytes)
\par    is terminated by a lacing value of 0.  Note also that a 'nil' (zero
\par    length) packet is not an error; it consists of nothing more than a
\par    lacing value of zero in the header.
\par 
