\par 
\par   A physical Ogg bitstream consists of a sequence of concatenated
\par    pages.  Pages are of variable size, usually 4-8 kB, maximum 65307
\par    bytes.  A page header contains all the information needed to
\par    demultiplex the logical bitstreams out of the physical bitstream and
\par    to perform basic error recovery and landmarks for seeking.  Each page
\par    is a self-contained entity such that the page decode mechanism can
\par    recognize, verify, and handle single pages at a time without
\par    requiring the overall bitstream.
\par 
\par   The LSb (least significant bit) comes first in the Bytes.  Fields
\par    with more than one byte length are encoded LSB (least significant
\par    byte) first.
\par 
\par    The total header size in bytes is given by:
\par    header_size = number_page_segments + 27 [Byte]
\par 
\par    The total page size in Bytes is given by:
\par    page_size = header_size + sum(lacing_values: 1..number_page_segments)
